The PyMC model introduces a dynamic alternation expectation. A sequence with a head probability $p$ mathematically has an expected alternation rate of $2p(1-p)$. This is equivalent to $1 - 4 \cdot \text{imbalance}^2$. In this model, we scale the subjective alternation ideal (`theta_alt`) by this exact factor, using the *smoothed* imbalance metric. This cleanly captures the intuition that highly imbalanced sequences (e.g. 9 Heads, 1 Tail) simply *cannot* have many alternations, avoiding inappropriately double-penalizing unbalanced sequences for lacking alternations.

